	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_921786">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_921786">This happens a lot in the US because databases are pretty much unregulated. The company that runs the computer the databases (or owns the filing cabinets the files are in) owns the data, not the person about whom the information is about. As a result, &quot;identity theft&quot; runs rampant in the US (about 50,000,000 IDs are stolen each year, and of those about 1,000,000 Americans per year become victims where someone actually uses that info for fraud). <br />
<br />
You've described what is called <i>the David Nelson Problem</i>. In short, some crook used david nelson as an alias. Long after he was arrested and thrown into jail, that name was added to the &quot;no fly list&quot; here in the US. As a result, every D. Nelson has to spend about 4 extra hours each way undergoing unnecessary scrutiny. There is no way to get that name off the list: because no single agency is accountable for the list. And that list is used also as a political weapon (which is why Senator Kennedy appeared on the list, and it took him several months to get it cleared up). <a href="http://www.schneier.com/" target="_blank">]Bruce Schneier</a> tends to talk about these sort of things/<br />
<br />
In the 2000 presidential election campaign, a private company, Choice Point, was hired to rid the Florida ballots of pesky brownskinned democrats. About 70,000 people were removed from the voter roles because <i>first name , last name</i> matched a felon's name, or they <i>first initial, last name, same birthday</i> was the match. It wasn't till after the election that these got cleared up, as each person had to individually prove that they weren't a felon. That list of ~70,000 names was 97% wrong. But the <i>mission accomplished</i> was to get the brother of the state governor selected president of the US.<br />
<br />
Databases where no one is accountable end up making the end consumer the liable party. In the past, in the US, banks used to mail credit cards to people even if they didn't fill out applications, then sue the people who weren't making payments. Congress put an end to that by making such credit cards uncollectable debt, and to put a financial limit on the effects of stolen credit cards (of $50). By putting those limits on credit card debt, the banks regulated themselves. They could do something like that now: if information is stolen out of <i>your</i> database, then <i>your</i> company becomes 100% liable for fraudulent transactions based on that information, or, if you issue debt to a fraudulent person, then that debt is uncollectable.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
